{
  "texts": [
    "Instead, I will argue that we may be on the verge of enacting not the death of the Author (or Man), but the birth of a nonhuman subjectivity, and that to make intellectual and practical progress we must interrogate this subjectivity as such.",
    "Material conditions and imperatives of a scientific, ideological and economic origin have played key roles in enabling the development of advanced generative AI models.",
    "As far as the connected person 6 is concerned, for example, the present may be characterised by an overarching obligation to document ourselves, exchange privacy for services, quantify the self and express ourselves-thereby recreating ourselves-in digital spaces.",
    "This obligation is influenced by narratives pitting privacy against security (Van Dijck 2014), the success of mathematical sciences (Van Dijck 2014), the corporate practice of bloated clickwrap agreements (Zuboff 2019), the invisibility of the algorithmic mechanisms (Weiskopf 2020), the neoliberal mantra to \"be yourself\" (Vassallo 2014), and also online-social factors of virtue signalling (Richey 2018); i.e.",
    "by coercive as well as emancipatory factors."
  ]
}